1
00:00:01,440 --> 00:00:03,720
a una grande quantità di persone.

2
00:00:04,680 --> 00:00:06,360
È il vostro lavoro, è il nostro lavoro,

3
00:00:06,560 --> 00:00:08,740
ma penso anche che dovremmo condividere le forze

4
00:00:08,740 --> 00:00:10,940
per, diciamo,

5
00:00:12,320 --> 00:00:14,300
per aiutare una migliore comprensione,

6
00:00:14,600 --> 00:00:17,920
almeno dalle due parti del Mediterraneo,

7
00:00:17,940 --> 00:00:22,600
che sarebbero già grandi come obiettivi.

8
00:00:23,120 --> 00:00:26,300
Grazie per ciò che stai facendo e per ciò che stai scrivendo.

9
00:00:31,940 --> 00:00:33,060
Thank you.

10
00:00:34,300 --> 00:00:36,240
Presidente, vuole la parola?

11
00:00:36,500 --> 00:00:37,260
Tocca a lei.

12
00:00:42,680 --> 00:00:45,460
You don't need it now.

13
00:00:48,260 --> 00:00:50,800
Ok, no, it's too much.

14
00:00:52,180 --> 00:00:53,660
No, no, no.

15
00:00:54,460 --> 00:00:58,260
No, first of all, I like the way you express yourself

16
00:00:58,260 --> 00:01:01,900
when you say, this is very important psychologically,

17
00:01:03,760 --> 00:01:05,780
the threat we are facing.

18
00:01:06,380 --> 00:01:09,720
You said and you wrote in a paper.

19
00:01:10,600 --> 00:01:15,300
It's important for, let's say, every kind of audience you meet

20
00:01:15,300 --> 00:01:18,680
or every kind of reader you have to understand

21
00:01:19,260 --> 00:01:22,740
that this is a common threat that we are facing

22
00:01:22,740 --> 00:01:27,240
and there is no difference between Muslim and non-Muslim,

23
00:01:27,240 --> 00:01:30,280
Christians, not Christians, whatever they are,

24
00:01:31,140 --> 00:01:36,220
in, let's say, the situation they find themselves

25
00:01:36,220 --> 00:01:40,580
vis-à-vis the fundamentalist kind of...

26
00:01:40,920 --> 00:01:41,940
It's a threat.

27
00:01:42,140 --> 00:01:46,200
It's a threat because independently of the connection,

28
00:01:46,380 --> 00:01:51,260
which you rightly not even underline too much,

29
00:01:51,420 --> 00:01:54,780
between fundamentalism and terrorism,

30
00:01:54,780 --> 00:01:58,120
which of course exists because there is a linkage.

31
00:01:58,660 --> 00:02:05,780
Terrorism finds reasons in this kind of monolithic interpretation

32
00:02:06,360 --> 00:02:10,240
of the Quran, but also independently of that.

33
00:02:10,700 --> 00:02:18,040
This kind of interpretation, this monolithic rigid interpretation

34
00:02:18,040 --> 00:02:25,380
is something that creates a profound divide

35
00:02:25,380 --> 00:02:30,840
between the societies which are prisoners

36
00:02:30,840 --> 00:02:34,240
of this kind of interpretation and any other.

37
00:02:35,060 --> 00:02:39,900
It is a threat for the Muslim world

38
00:02:39,900 --> 00:02:47,340
because of course it is a rightly fragmented word.

39
00:02:48,220 --> 00:02:51,740
You don't have a hierarchical structure

40
00:02:51,740 --> 00:02:55,360
such as other religions have,

41
00:02:55,900 --> 00:02:59,700
and therefore it makes sense to have different communities.

42
00:03:00,380 --> 00:03:04,540
Of course, if the only interpretation of the Quran

43
00:03:04,540 --> 00:03:10,070
is the ummah that has everything in itself,

44
00:03:10,800 --> 00:03:15,930
the risk of not differences but conflicts is enormous

45
00:03:16,060 --> 00:03:19,730
inside the Muslim world and obviously

46
00:03:20,060 --> 00:03:24,940
between Muslim individuals, groups, communities,

47
00:03:25,240 --> 00:03:28,760
and non-Muslim communities living close to each other

48
00:03:28,760 --> 00:03:32,200
in whatever part of the world.

49
00:03:32,200 --> 00:03:39,320
How can I establish a peaceful relationship with the other one

50
00:03:39,320 --> 00:03:46,120
if the other one, being not a believer, is an enemy of mine?

51
00:03:47,380 --> 00:03:54,440
This is crucial, not being linked by that kind,

52
00:03:54,520 --> 00:03:58,820
and therefore it is a threat that we are facing.

53
00:04:00,220 --> 00:04:04,100
The kind of work that you are doing,

54
00:04:04,320 --> 00:04:09,320
which as Emma said is really a very precious kind of work,

55
00:04:11,380 --> 00:04:16,760
is extremely useful toward the non-Muslim

56
00:04:16,760 --> 00:04:24,040
just in saying and repeating, even though we are saying and repeating

57
00:04:24,040 --> 00:04:27,860
that the Muslim world is not monolithic.

58
00:04:28,220 --> 00:04:31,100
There are different interpretations, etc.

59
00:04:32,580 --> 00:04:36,720
I don't know whether you are familiar with the Italian press

60
00:04:36,720 --> 00:04:40,740
and the editorials that appear, but until a couple of years ago,

61
00:04:41,600 --> 00:04:46,900
the leading newspaper of the country published editorials

62
00:04:46,900 --> 00:04:51,380
in which you could read that moderate Islam does not exist,

63
00:04:51,380 --> 00:04:55,100
that we would be happy to deal with,

64
00:04:55,540 --> 00:05:01,880
but this is an invention of the Italian left, substantially.

65
00:05:05,520 --> 00:05:09,400
Difficult to digest because so far from truth,

66
00:05:10,140 --> 00:05:18,320
and therefore it makes sense also for us to have somebody giving evidence

67
00:05:18,320 --> 00:05:23,660
that this is completely nonsense as I think,

68
00:05:23,700 --> 00:05:29,620
but it is clear that you, I might be wrong,

69
00:05:30,300 --> 00:05:35,640
are mostly speaking to Muslim readers,

70
00:05:36,060 --> 00:05:41,860
somehow explaining to them that the holy text

71
00:05:41,860 --> 00:05:48,840
has to be interpreted within historical contexts.

72
00:05:49,760 --> 00:05:54,960
This is what is essential just to accept

73
00:05:54,960 --> 00:06:00,720
that the substantial meaning of these words

74
00:06:00,720 --> 00:06:06,360
does not necessarily correspond to the traditionally accepted meaning

75
00:06:06,360 --> 00:06:09,800
or even to the literary meaning of these words.

76
00:06:09,800 --> 00:06:15,020
This is an exercise that has been, if you want,

77
00:06:18,240 --> 00:06:23,940
repeatedly accomplished in relation to the holy text of other religions,

78
00:06:24,560 --> 00:06:30,840
and paradoxically it is an old exercise also for the Koran.

79
00:06:31,720 --> 00:06:33,000
It's not new.

80
00:06:33,460 --> 00:06:39,680
This is quite a paradox because if you are not thinking in historical terms,

81
00:06:39,680 --> 00:06:44,840
you might discover that between the Koran and the Sharia

82
00:06:44,840 --> 00:06:49,260
there is a difference as something completely new,

83
00:06:49,820 --> 00:06:56,020
while only a thousand years ago it was already written, said and practiced.

84
00:06:57,400 --> 00:07:02,080
And this too has to be somehow considered.

85
00:07:04,460 --> 00:07:10,360
I wonder, something that is interesting for me is,

86
00:07:10,360 --> 00:07:14,780
and it should also become a part of the exercise,

87
00:07:15,200 --> 00:07:21,280
is a sort of comparative religion in the sense that other religions,

88
00:07:21,900 --> 00:07:24,320
the interpretation of other holy texts,

89
00:07:25,060 --> 00:07:31,240
how much they correspond to the kind of issues that you are tackling or not.

90
00:07:31,240 --> 00:07:37,040
I would say that in the Christian world this kind of position,

91
00:07:37,920 --> 00:07:41,800
there is one only interpretation of the holy book,

92
00:07:42,300 --> 00:07:45,520
is very minoritarian, it's very limited.

93
00:07:45,880 --> 00:07:49,840
You have some American minoritarian groups.

94
00:07:51,180 --> 00:07:55,200
All of us know about children whose parents,

95
00:07:56,660 --> 00:08:01,300
think that the only possible teaching has to be consistent

96
00:08:01,300 --> 00:08:03,460
with the literary meaning of the Bible.

97
00:08:04,260 --> 00:08:07,220
And therefore there is no possible school for these children

98
00:08:07,220 --> 00:08:10,320
because in any other book there is something new,

99
00:08:11,140 --> 00:08:14,220
that the Bible of course could not anticipate

100
00:08:14,220 --> 00:08:17,820
for obvious reasons from your angle.

101
00:08:17,820 --> 00:08:21,640
So really in relation to this,

102
00:08:23,520 --> 00:08:27,660
the acceptance inside the Muslim world

103
00:08:27,660 --> 00:08:31,860
of a literary interpretation of the Koran,

104
00:08:32,040 --> 00:08:35,560
the difficult distinction between the Koran and the Shamiya,

105
00:08:35,700 --> 00:08:39,780
is something that I would consider wider nowadays

106
00:08:39,780 --> 00:08:42,400
than it is in the Christian world.

107
00:08:42,400 --> 00:08:49,360
While the other aspects that you were highlighting

108
00:08:49,360 --> 00:08:56,100
in your presentation of the fundamentalist doctrine,

109
00:08:57,000 --> 00:09:03,540
namely any social and political issue has been theologized,

110
00:09:03,540 --> 00:09:10,620
you said, well this is a trend that is not so minoritarian

111
00:09:12,620 --> 00:09:16,880
as you could think in other religions,

112
00:09:18,160 --> 00:09:22,540
because it might be due to the fact that increasingly

113
00:09:23,140 --> 00:09:27,960
issues that are dealt with in the political sphere

114
00:09:27,960 --> 00:09:35,380
have some sort of connection with matters of religious belief,

115
00:09:36,040 --> 00:09:38,780
one reason or another I don't know,

116
00:09:39,240 --> 00:09:44,400
but the fact is that issues which are being discussed

117
00:09:44,400 --> 00:09:50,820
in the public sphere, in relation to which there is a position

118
00:09:50,820 --> 00:09:56,740
that is considered correct from a religious angle,

119
00:09:56,740 --> 00:10:02,100
these issues are, let's say, increasing in number.

120
00:10:04,440 --> 00:10:09,960
And here too, it becomes also for other religions,

121
00:10:10,740 --> 00:10:14,020
it is becoming increasingly important to distinguish

122
00:10:14,020 --> 00:10:19,800
between the word of God and the word of the, let's say,

123
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:22,120
believers or of the hierarchy.

124
00:10:22,120 --> 00:10:27,520
This is an exercise that is extremely important,

125
00:10:27,760 --> 00:10:35,180
how much we owe what in Latin they call credenda

126
00:10:35,180 --> 00:10:42,000
to the fact that they are immediately drawn from the words of God,

127
00:10:42,480 --> 00:10:44,920
the Bible and or the Gospel,

128
00:10:45,580 --> 00:10:50,300
when the credenda are something due to the hierarchy

129
00:10:50,300 --> 00:10:56,740
and therefore to the Pope, to his positions,

130
00:10:57,480 --> 00:11:02,840
and have these two kind of credenda the same value,

131
00:11:03,480 --> 00:11:07,340
these two is an extremely important issue.

132
00:11:12,920 --> 00:11:19,800
I conclusively go back to the question I was asking

133
00:11:19,800 --> 00:11:21,440
Emma before.

134
00:11:22,640 --> 00:11:28,620
There is a clear relationship between openness of societies

135
00:11:28,620 --> 00:11:35,380
and, let's say, tolerant interpretation of religious texts

136
00:11:35,380 --> 00:11:39,000
and religious credenda generally.

137
00:11:39,760 --> 00:11:42,080
What comes first?

138
00:11:42,500 --> 00:11:48,860
This interpretation more tolerant makes societies more open

139
00:11:48,860 --> 00:11:52,400
or being a society more open,

140
00:11:52,640 --> 00:11:56,620
the interpretation of holy texts is more tolerant.

141
00:12:00,600 --> 00:12:03,180
It's a two-way process, I suppose.

142
00:12:03,500 --> 00:12:07,720
It's difficult, so we have to imagine these as a circle

143
00:12:08,540 --> 00:12:16,180
that is virtuous somehow and difficult to identify the chicken

144
00:12:16,180 --> 00:12:21,640
and identify the egg in this kind of process,

145
00:12:22,700 --> 00:12:30,840
but what in my view is also important is to understand the sense

146
00:12:30,840 --> 00:12:36,320
of the more tolerant interpretation of religious credenda

147
00:12:36,320 --> 00:12:39,580
typical of more open societies.

148
00:12:39,800 --> 00:12:45,140
Does this mean that they are less religious or not?

149
00:12:45,140 --> 00:12:55,460
Yesterday, in the course of the beautiful conference on Aldo Moro

150
00:12:55,460 --> 00:12:59,740
in the 30th anniversary of his death,

151
00:12:59,940 --> 00:13:06,240
a very serious kind of thing with panels highly qualified,

152
00:13:06,240 --> 00:13:16,240
a professor of the Kennedy Government School of Harvard,

153
00:13:16,500 --> 00:13:23,500
Pippa Norris, was presenting her future book on cultural convergence,

154
00:13:24,440 --> 00:13:30,560
a book to be published by Oxford or Cambridge Press generally

155
00:13:30,560 --> 00:13:34,360
was written three years before, as all of us know.

156
00:13:34,360 --> 00:13:41,060
Therefore, she was eager to present the book a year before the publication.

157
00:13:42,960 --> 00:13:53,640
Basically, by using data on practicing religious rights, etc., etc.,

158
00:13:54,180 --> 00:14:03,020
she was concluding that God is for traditional and backward societies,

159
00:14:03,960 --> 00:14:08,400
substantially. She didn't say so, but this was the substance of the argument.

160
00:14:09,240 --> 00:14:16,720
So as soon as a society gets more modern, more open, etc.,

161
00:14:16,720 --> 00:14:19,360
religiousness goes down.

162
00:14:21,040 --> 00:14:25,960
I humbly objected that it is not necessarily so.

163
00:14:26,880 --> 00:14:31,540
And I said, I'm not a believer, so I'm not speaking of me,

164
00:14:31,540 --> 00:14:39,940
but I understand that religion becomes, in an open society,

165
00:14:40,540 --> 00:14:48,480
something that is more led from inside than from religious hierarchies.

166
00:14:49,820 --> 00:14:56,360
And this is part of the more openness of society.

167
00:14:56,360 --> 00:15:04,780
And therefore I am convinced there are many more religious people in Italy

168
00:15:04,780 --> 00:15:09,940
than those who go every Sunday to worship.

169
00:15:13,220 --> 00:15:24,360
I wonder whether we can elaborate some more on these kind of issues,

170
00:15:24,360 --> 00:15:32,060
because you might easily find yourself in the same position in which,

171
00:15:32,100 --> 00:15:39,460
let's say, the Catholic liberals, I would call them like this,

172
00:15:39,760 --> 00:15:45,360
find themselves in countries like mine or in Spain

173
00:15:45,360 --> 00:15:50,800
or where there is a strong religious hierarchy.

174
00:15:50,800 --> 00:16:03,040
I mean, you are saying that religion has become a sort of individual affair,

175
00:16:03,560 --> 00:16:08,920
that it has been individualized as any other aspect of life,

176
00:16:09,620 --> 00:16:14,720
but you are substantially speaking on behalf of an atheist society,

177
00:16:14,720 --> 00:16:15,980
where...

